Because StreamEx is powerful, I am switching over to returning streams from methods and passing streams as arguments instead of using `List`.  In several situations, this avoids having to convert a stream into a `List`, return the `List` and then only to have the caller create a stream from the `List`.

My use case has a stream passed as an argument to a method.  The stream is going to be put into a `Properties` object which is then going to be stored on disk.  The keys are a combination of a prefix and the index.

```
private static final String RECENT_PREFIX = "recent.";
private static final int RECENT_LIMIT = 10;

private static void setRecent(Properties properties, StreamEx<File> recent)
{
   StreamEx<String> keys;
   long count;

   keys = IntStreamEx.
      range(0, RECENT_LIMIT).
      mapToObj(index -> RECENT_PREFIX + index);

   count = StreamUtils.
      zip(keys, recent).                            // Creates an EntryStream<String, File>
      mapValues(File::getAbsolutePath).
      peekKeyValue(properties::setProperty).
      count();

   IntStreamEx.
      range((int) count, RECENT_LIMIT).
      mapToObj(index -> RECENT_PREFIX + index).
      forEach(properties::remove);
}
```

As you suggested, I could create a `KeyFile` object.  However, I am not sure how to create the keys while going through the recent stream.

